4. **Inequality $\phi(n) > \phi(n - \phi(n)) + f(n)$**: We need to show that $\phi(n) - \phi(n - \phi(n)) > f(n)$ for almost all $n$. 

5. **Asymptotic behavior**: Since $f(n) = o(n)$, we have $f(n) / n \to 0$ as $n \to \infty$. 

6. **Key theorem**: We need to show that $\phi(n) - \phi(n - \phi(n))$ is large enough to exceed $f(n)$ for large $n$. 

7. **Result from number theory**: It is known from the theory of arithmetic functions that $\phi(n) - \phi(n - \phi(n))$ is usually large. In fact, it is known that $\phi(n) > \phi(n - \phi(n))$ for all $n \geq 2$ (this can be checked for small values). 

8. **Further result**: More precisely, it is known that $\phi(n) - \phi(n - \phi(n)) \geq \Omega(n / \log n)$, which is much larger than $o(n)$. 

